tool.name: ReclassByTableRasterTool

param.name: raster_table
param.dialogReference: This is the input table, usually the results table generated by the ‘Geodata > Search’ tool, but it can be any table with a field containing the full path to the raster datasets you want to process with this tool. If the results table is a DBF, or a table in an ESRI File Geodatabase, then you can select a subset of rows in ArcMap and only those rows will be processed by the tool.

param.name: raster_table_field_geodata
param.dialogReference: Select the field from the 'Table for Rasters' that contains the full path to the raster items you want to process.

param.name: in_remap_table
param.dialogReference:
Table holding fields defining value ranges to be reclassified and the values they will become. See the Table below for an example of a 'Remap table’ that reclassifies a raster dataset from 0-100 range to integer classes 1-4.

From

To

Output

0

25

1

26

50

2

51

75

3

76

100

4

TIP #1: You need to create this table. The most common method to do this is to copy the raster attribute table and add extra fields to it, i.e. add the ‘From’, ‘To’ and ‘Output’ fields.

TIP #2: To reclassify individual values, use a simple remap table of two fields. The first field identifies the value to reclassify, and the other field identifies the value to assign to it. Set the 'To’ field value the same as the 'From’ field value. The value to assign to the output is 'Output’ field value.

param.name: missing_values
param.dialogReference:
Denotes whether missing values in the reclass table retain their value or get mapped to NoData. Select from:

  • DATA — Signifies that if any cell location on the input raster contains a value not present or reclassed in a remap table, the value should remain intact and be written for that location to the output raster. This is the default.

  • NODATA — Signifies that if any cell location on the input raster contains a value not present or reclassed in a remap table, the value will be reclassed to NoData for that location on the output raster.

param.name: raster_format
param.dialogReference: Raster format for output geodata. You can choose from: Esri Grid, img (ERDAS IMAGINE) or tif (GeoTIFF). If you select a file geodatabase for the Result Workspace then the output format will default to ‘Esri Grid’. When storing your raster geodata to a JPEG file, a JPEG 2000 file, a TIFF file, or a geodatabase, you can specify a compression type and compression quality within the ‘Environment Settings’.

param.name: output_workspace
param.dialogReference:
This is the location for the Grid Garage results table containing the list of raster datasets processed by the tool as well as any data outputs. If the tool encounters any errors when processing the input raster datasets then a second results table will be generated, with a "_FAIL" suffix, listing the input raster datasets that failed and any ESRI error messages.

If you have set the ArcGIS ‘Workspace' parameter in the 'Geoprocessing > Environment' Settings then this path will be used as the default. You can use this default path or click the folder button to select a new output location which can be a folder or File Geodatabase. If you specify a folder then the Results Table will be written to a comma-delimited (CSV) text file, if you specify a File Geodatabase it will be written as a Geodatabase Table.

param.name: output_filename_prefix
param.dialogReference: Any text you enter in this input box will be added as a prefix (at the beginning) for all output file names.

param.name: output_filename_suffix
param.dialogReference: Any text you enter in this input box will be added as a suffix (at the end) for all output file names.

param.name: result_table_name
param.dialogReference:
You can choose to use the default table name or specify a different name for the Grid Garage results table. The Grid Garage results table contains the list of raster datasets processed by the tool.

If the tool encounters any errors when processing any of the raster datasets then a second results table will be generated, with a "_FAIL" suffix, listing the input raster datasets that failed and any ESRI error messages. If you choose a folder for the Output Workspace then the result table will be written to a comma-delimited (CSV) text file which will not allow you to select rows for processing when using the table as input for other Grid Garage Tools.

Result Table file name: The default name will always take the form of “ReclassByTableRasterTool_date_time”, where ‘date’ and ‘time’ are the date and time that the tool was run.

tool.summary:
This tool Reclassifies (or changes) the values of the input cells of a raster using a remap table.The tool uses the standard ArcGIS ‘Reclass by Table (Spatial Analyst)’ tool. For more detailed help see ESRI Help for the ‘Reclass by Table (Spatial Analyst)’ tool.
